20 weeks 🥹✨ we’ve made it so far baby bean!

you don’t even know yet but so many people already love you so much and are working so hard to make sure you enter this world safe with mom & dad. You’re so loved, baby 💓

Mom’s journey to get you here hasn’t been a easy road and I can’t wait to tell you about it one day.

🫶🏼 #disabledparentpower

When you are pregnant the first thing everybody asks you is: boy or a girl?!

And it is super exciting finding out and knowing, and we wanted to share that with everybody. While finding out if the baby is a boy or a girl is exciting, we are more so excited to just be parents and start a family.

Having a high-risk pregnancy while being disabled has been one of the most challenging things I have ever been through and the fact that I get to be a mother is what matters most to us, our families, and friends.

So we decided to have a very small celebration where we tell our family and friends if baby is a boy or a girl and just celebrate baby & all it’s taking to get her here!

With all that being said, for now we have a daughter. What we wish for our daughter is to raise her in a way that culminates her individuality and autonomy. Whatever she decides to identify as when she is older, we are both going to be completely supportive of whatever she chooses 🫶🏼

Mommy to be 💓 We have a name picked, when am I supposed to tell y’all?! 🥰

I want to thank all my friends that were able to make our baby celebration and a huge thank you to @coreylibera & @jeziej for helping with setup 💓🫶🏼

My heart is so full & our baby girl is so lucky to have these amazing people in her life 🫶🏼

I’ve been feeling good and my potassium is back to normal!

My biggest craving is still MAC N CHEESE 🧀 💓🫶🏼🎉

I can definitely feel her getting bigger it seems almost daily! She loves to kick me all the time & honestly it is such a weird feeling and I’m not particularly keen on it 😂 any other moms feel like that?! It feels so uncomfortable!

My genetic testing results came in today and baby tested negative for everything, so we’re just waiting on the SMA carrier screening to come back.

I have a OB apt tomorrow for just a check up, things are moving along!

IT’S STARTING TO FEEL SO REAL, I love her so much 💕

Disabled pregnancy power 💗 23 weeks today! #EndTheStigma

Let’s body shame people then hate on face altering apps… the logic?

I was accused of using Facetune in one of my photos that I recently posted when I did not. I do use apps to alter the color and clarity of the photo to make it a more cohesive, vibrant piece. That isn’t to say that I haven’t used Facetune in the past.

Many creators use apps that alter their face and body, and I know firsthand that it can lead to a slippery slope.

instead of hating on Facetune, we should be talking about why people feel the need to even use it in the first place.

recently, people have been body shaming me about my teeth, my nose, my oily skin, fingernails, my feet, etc.

does it hurt my feelings at times? Yes. I am a human being and I do have feelings.

an easy solution? ‘fix’ these things with one swipe on an app. And that is what I used to do and what many people still do.

but, I have been on my body image confidence journey for years now and I do not feel the need to edit a photo or hide my dirty fingernails because strangers on the Internet are you going to pass judgment on me.

yes, my teeth are yellow and my front tooth is black because it is dead from a root canal I had years ago. Can I get it fixed? Absolutely. But I haven’t which means it is clearly not a priority to me. I do not find my worth in how white or perfect my teeth appear.

have I gotten lip filler? Yes I have. Was I confident without it? Yes I was. Did I do it to placate body shaming? No.

would I rather spend money on decorating my apartment than making my teeth pearly white? Clearly yes! 

That’s where I find joy.

I do not find joy in changing my appearance based on body shaming trolls.
Noah’s SMA carrier results are in! Watch until the end❤️

Christmas decor, apartment decor update, Bubba & @noahsmithya looking precious, and our precious embroidered stockings from Noah’s mom AND my mom’s amazing organizational skills on our closet ❄️🎄

Today is also me & Noah’s 8 month anniversary 🎊

Week 24 🎊 Officially viable!

Since the beginning of my pregnancy the Internet has doubted my parenting ability in the form of thousands of comments I receive every day on multiple platforms. Or that my baby will not make it to viability purely based on the fact that I am disabled. 

It’s funny because the main thing people bring up is that I am not going to be able to change a diaper.

As if that simplistic task is the corner stone of raising a well rounded, happy child.

I can’t wipe my own butt, that doesn’t mean that I don’t facilitate that task getting done.

When it comes to disabled people being in relationships and parenting it seems like the main focus is on the physicality.

“what if your partner wants to go on a hike?”
“how will you change a diaper!”
“your partner will have to do everything for you“
“how will you feed the baby?”
“you can’t even move during sex“

The list goes on and on. I never see comments like, disabled people are extremely resourceful. Or.. disabled people are very creative and independent which has taught them how to get the job done. Or disabled people are great partners and intimacy is expressed on a spectrum.

In the grand scheme of parenting, changing a diaper is probably one of the least important things that a child will carry with them when they’re older and developing their sense of self.

It seems like when I am doing what society expects me to do, which is entertain and educate on disability… I receive praise.

But, when I decide that I want to have a relationship and start a family… something that disabled people are stigmatized for doing, I am villainized.

I do not exist in this space to placate the abled-gaze. I do not wish to promote an us, them atmosphere.

I exist in this space to disrupt the status quo. To start the conversations.

To question what you think you know about disability.
First Christmas as a couple. First Christmas pregnant. Last Christmas without our baby girl in our photos 💓🥹

26 weeks , 4 days 🥰 I have a rare genetic disease.

Both my parents were SMA carriers, unknowingly. I had a 25% chance of being affected… & we all know I was that 25%. I am so incredibly happy I was born and have the life that I do.

Life is rare and precious.

I was told by a genetic counselor that we each unknowingly carry at least 5 genetic diseases. And those can be passed on if you decide to have children. That’s not to say you shouldn’t give birth because your child might be disabled. Or inherent a disease you don’t even know you carry.

That’s eugenics.

Throughout my pregnancy I’ve been called selfish and cruel because there’s this assumption that because I’m disabled my child will be disabled.

While nothing is for sure, every test and scan that we have done point to our daughter being born non disabled.

& still, the assumption persists. Despite sharing this. They get one look at my disabled pregnant belly & automatically think something will go ‘wrong’ or that our baby will be born disabled.

Whether or not our daughter is born with a disability we aren’t aware of yet or acquires a disability later in life, she will be loved just the same. 

So this is your official reminder that disabled people can and do give birth to non-disabled children 🫶🏼

And that is the journey. That is life. That is love.

My new look 😋 So, I spoke too soon — I started feeling off today so we checked my oxygen level & heart rate — oxygen was lower than usual and heart rate was high.

It looks like what my doctors had warned me would be inevitable is starting to happen. My lungs have been working overtime especially with my uterus growing larger and compressing my little disabled lungs.

That is why we have my ventilator setup prepped for situations like this. So, I’m mobile & can breathe, woo! After putting on my vent I felt so much better and my oxygen went back up.

What does this all mean?
I might need to be wearing the vent more often throughout the day. I might need to be admitted to the hospital while cooking baby girl just to be monitored and get oxygen.

We see our OB Tuesday & will discuss what the game plan is going forward. If I can stay at home and support my breathing with wearing the vent more for a while, we’ll do that. If doc wants to admit me to be safe, we’ll do that!

She made it clear just because I’m admitted doesn’t mean I’ll deliver. That’s a multiteam decision!

For now, we’ll keep you updated!

So happy that my nipples almost started leaking 🤰🏼🥹💓 (that actually has happened, btw) this bassinet is absolutely perfect for wheelchair access and I am so excited to be finding accessible options to help me be as involved in my daughters care as possible!
Baby girl is lucky to have noah as her daddy 🥰💓

29 weeks in 2 days (the day of my 29th birthday party) 🥰✨ I had my lil disabled lungs checked today by my pulmonologist & they’re chugging along! Had a lung function test & I’m at the same capacity as I was at 16 weeks. Very good news & a relief to say the least 🎉

we talked more about me being sedated for a bit after surgery, waking me up, & extubation — it’s so encouraging how reassuring & confident my pulmonologist is about the entire process.

The team is in place. And we’re looking at the week of march 13th for delivery…. AHHHHH ❤️
Coming March 2023 💓

social_posts.post_text: Mom & dad🫶🏼🤰🏼

LAST YEAR IN MY 20’s 🎉

I had such an amazing birthday party and I am so thankful for the people in my life. My friends are truly just amazing individuals and my heart is so full 🫶🏼💗

I want to give an extra special thank you to my new assistant Nina and my amazing boyfriend for putting this beautiful celebration together… they both worked together to plan this entire thing without me and it came out just spectacular✨

The highlight of my night was definitely watching the boys dance LOL — i’ll be posting more bday content on my stories if you want to check it out hehe it’s pretty funny 😋

29th birthday party on the day I turned 29 weeks pregnant so much to celebrate!

Jumpsuit I’m wearing was gifted by @prettylittlething from their maternity selection💓
Birthday decor ✨🌸🧁 BY @ninaanndecker & @noahsmithya
It’s the hip thrusts for me 😂🥰💓

31 weeks feeling you grow from the comfort of my wheelchair. Growing in mommy day by day, getting stronger for the day you enter this harsh world. But don’t worry, Baby A, because mommy & daddy and your grandparents and your aunties and uncles love you so much and will guide you on your path.

Whoever you end up to be, your journey here is something I’ll cherish the rest of my life.

Mom & dad are patiently (kinda 🤪) awaiting your arrival.

4 more weeks 💓

📷 @ninaanndecker

32 WEEKS & we are finally nearing the end of the road friends! Pregnancy has brought a lot of firsts for me… including getting to swing around in a Hoyer lift 😝

it is officially that time… My body is telling me that we cannot handle much more so I am being monitored very very closely and I am doing very well, just a few little things and we are preparing for delivery of baby A!

maybe have gotten six hours of sleep in the past two days but I am running on adrenaline and excitement at this point! Got my first dose of steroids to speed up lung development in baby!

I am being monitored for possible preeclampsia, but all my blood work is slowly showing improvement not that anything was super bad just a little off here and there! All pregnancy related.

baby a is also being monitored daily and she is doing great— I talked with my team today and we all decided that if my platelets go back up that I can hopefully go home tomorrow and try to push for one more week, as my respiratory status is hanging tough and I am feeling better! I needed a bit of oxygen just while I was sleeping because my oxygen goes down just a little bit when I am sleeping or lying down because there is so much pressure.

When I am in my wheelchair, all my vitals are perfect! So I am just waiting on some test results and hopefully I can go home tomorrow if my doctor says I can so that we can cook her for one more week 💓 if my platelets are the same or lower we will go ahead with a sooner delivery!

SHE’S GOING TO BE HERE SO SOON!

“I can’t I’m busy growing a human” 🥰🤪 MOOD UNTIL DELIVERY🎉 I get to go home today! Still having some minor medical things that I can deal with from home, I got the go ahead from my team to rest stop at home and still get blood work done at my OB appointment on Tuesday to make sure that I am staying stable before my C-section which we are trying to plan very strategically but we are thinking it will probably be within the next week! So, I get to rest and prepare from the comfort of my own home which is amazing as long as there are no changes!

The nursing staff, my medical team, and the floor team, and the OB/GYN team, has been absolutely incredible throughout this entire process that in other words could have been so much more stressful if I didn’t have such amazing healthcare professionals working with me!

I am extremely uncomfortable and nourishing my body is getting very difficult, so the plan is to rest, nourish myself, and prepare for the c-section.

if all goes as planned, which we know that can change by the hour, we are hoping to go to 33 weeks!

HOME STRETCH! 🫶🏼💓

not to be that person but I wanted to add that I showed my high-risk OB/GYN the nursery and asked her if the canopy is in any way unsafe… And they all started laughing. And I mentioned airflow and any reasons y’all have been sending me unsolicited DMs about. So, the high-risk OB/GYN has put her medical seal of approval on my canopy, so wheelchair Rapunzel canopygate can be put to rest lol 🫡

Baby A’s canopy is whimsical, gorgeous, and peaceful & that’s all that needs said on that 🌸✨💫

I’M HOME 🎉🥰 after being poked probably 5-6 times daily for three days, multiple veins blown bc im an impossible stick, a slew of tests, and no rest — momma is getting some much needed rest in my own bed!

I have been getting flooded with messages and I cannot thank you enough for your support 💓🫶🏼💫 I would reply to each and every one of you if I could.

as soon as I know an official delivery date I will let you know! I am doing every day in my power to give her the best chance and try & go another week. Even tho I’m in a lot of pain and discomfort. We’re trucking along!

Hoping to know more about a delivery date on Tuesday at my follow up 🤰🏼💕

Swipe for a huge milestone! Was planning a lame cake photoshoot to celebrate before I was admitted to the hospital… is it too late? Maybe if im up to it I’ll pull it off?! 😝

UPDATED C SECTION DATE 💫 momma has been through it.

everything hurts, breathing is hard, I can barely eat or drink, but we are finally almost there.

it seems like there is a new plan every single day and that in it of itself has been really stressful, just the uncertainty of it all.

can I go longer? Am I at the end of the road? What are the risks? What’s the risk between me and baby?

choosing the perfect time to deliver that is safe for me and baby is like threading a fine needle through a haystack.

I have been dealing with serious dehydration and until I deliver, I need to get IV fluids every other day. Honestly, they have been making me feel so much better and it is also just frustrating because I spend all day trying to intake liquid and it doesn’t seem to do much. 

my OB/GYN and I both agreed that we want to go another week putting us at 34 weeks to give baby A the best chance while I am still able to medically intervene at home.

although it is hard to breathe, my respiratory status is stable. This extra week is going to improve her chances dramatically from infection and other lung interventions that she might need as a preemie.

as much as I want to say no just please do it now I can’t handle this, I want my daughter coming into the world as safe and healthy as she can be.

March 3rd, here we come 💓✨

until then, I am going to need a lot of distractions. Send me any recommendations in the comments 🥹🥰🤰🏼💕
Something I’m most excited for… to see baby A & her daddy together 🥲 He’s going to be such an amazing dad & we are so thankful baby A chose us to be her parents 💫

32 weeks + 6 days 💫 at this point, every single day is such a win! Today I woke up in really good spirits feeling pretty energetic which is so refreshing from how I have been feeling.

I am still being closely monitored and got some more bloodwork done today and had an NST done on baby A and she’s doing great!

we moved my C-section date to March 6 so that my pulmonologist can be there during my extubation (instead of his associate). He promised Noah and I that he would be there to support us and hold my hand during what he knows is going to be a scary thing for me, and we really appreciate that. My doctors that are familiar with me know that I have really bad anxiety and panic disorder so they really want me to have as much support and comfort as possible during the extubation.

everything changes daily lol but if we keep this C-section date and everything goes as planned from here on out, she will be born at 34 weeks +2 days. We are doing everything in our power to keep me good so that I can keep cooking up our precious little bean as long as my body will allow while considering both of our safety💓

for now, she is arriving into the world on March 6 🤰🏼💓

also, Noah’s clothes are the only clothes that fit me currently & im not mad bc they are COZY AS HECK😂
Feeling a lot better after hydration! 33 weeks today 🎉💓🤰🏼🥰❤️🌸
1 week until her scheduled delivery, 33 weeks + 2 days. Love marks of a pregnant disabled body 💫✨💕🌸
A accurate depiction of how excited I am to meet her in just 6 more days 🤰🏼💕❤️🎉🌸🥰
Mom mode: activated 🥹💕🌸
Parents 🫶🏼

Coming up on 3 weeks since our sweet pea has been in the NICU — each day when I have to leave her, it gets harder & harder. We are so eager to get her home, but little miss is still growing and learning her feeds! She’s been doing so amazing and is so strong! 5 lb 3 oz today 🎉🫶🏼

Until we get her home, NICU cuddles will have to suffice 💓
Hi, my new mom hobby is interior design 💁🏼‍♀️
Favorite part of my day 🥰💕
My entire heart ♥️ The way she looks at mommy 🥹
My person 💕
Mini me ♥️
Passed her car seat test 🎉💓
She is home 🥹🎉💓✨
At home in our arms where she belongs 💓

From the minute I knew you existed, I loved you.

Growing in mommy’s belly made my muscles weaker, but feeling your little feet kick me made me smile, even when I didn’t feel good.

The entire time you were in mommy’s belly, I dreamed about how you would look and who you would be.

I dreamt of beautiful blue eyes that are as blue as the ocean. I dreamt of you hugging me and being nestled in my arms, safe and sound.

& now I can say, my dream has come true 💓

Diaries of a disabled mom 🌻

The joy I feel caring for my daughter is nothing I’ve ever felt before.

As someone who lives life relying on the help of others to get my basic needs met, it’s rare that I have the opportunity to physically care for any of my loved ones.

Not discounting my ability to care for people in other ways, but physically holding my baby girl and helping her nourish her little body is pure bliss.

It’s independence.

I was unsure of how proactive I was going to be able to be with her physical care, especially with all the comments that were seeping into my brain everyday, “you can’t even move your arms, you won’t be able to feed her”

With some patience, innovation, and brainstorming — I’m able to do a lot of her care.

Especially her feeds.

Disabled motherhood is one of the most emotional, amazing, joyful journeys I’ve ever been on. And we are glad you are here to witness it 💓
My mini me 💓🌸💕✨

One year with you 💓 only managed to get this low quality mirror picture 🤣 #parentlife 

I love you beyond words, Noah. Here’s to many more years together raising our beautiful daughter 💕
Mom on the go 🌻🌞💕
How is she getting so big 🥹💕 My heart melts when Noah holds her & she’s so tiny compared to him. We love her beyond words 🌻
Now, a year later, we are happier than ever with a beautiful daughter we are so blessed to have 💓 The best things in life are messy and unplanned. I love our love and she is a product of that.
Girls day 💓 Ari got to meet all of her beautiful sisters (not blood, our close family friends) & she can’t wait for pool days and barbecues at the farm 🌞
We call her our little beef hamlet 🥰

Mommy daughter spa day 🧖🏼‍♀️ ✨💓

I am always looking for ways I can interact and bond with my baby girl as a disabled mom. One way we do that together is by having spa days!

We LOVE using the @soluxuryinc coconut and oat milk bath. This soak completely replaces traditional soap, so only this product is needed from head to toe which makes it very accessible for me with Ari! All ingredients are also 100% certified organic.

AND they even have a mommy and me set 🤗💓

So here’s my PSA to treat yourself to a spa day, you deserve it 🫶🏼
Putting my wheelchair on glass over the side of the 103rd floor was not scary at all 🫣🥲
The beauty of disabled motherhood 🌻
First family beach day in the books 🌞
Summer in Chicago makes the cold winter so worth it 🌞✨🥰

The 1st time I’ve gotten my hair done since being pregnant.

It sounds silly, but this day meant a lot to me. It was transformative in the way that during my pregnancy I felt very much brittle and dry and now I feel glowy and blossomy.

Transcending into motherhood from pregnancy if you will.

Renewed.
Rejuvenated.

As my uterus gets accustomed to unhousing life, my skin is reproducing the oils and glow baby Ari was nourishing out of me.

My hair is becoming less brittle, more bright.

I find the dichotomy picturesque — a beautiful life that’s unseen, growing, flourishing, as my outer body deteriorates.

My daughter being born, my skin and hair coming back to life.

Mother and daughter — full of life

Being able to drive my wheelchair while holding Ari is one of the most liberating things I have experienced in a while.

Disabled motherhood has definitely not been easy, especially figuring out ways that I can be involved with her care and interact with her as much as I can — and when I find a new way, or a product that helps me assist in that, it puts such brightness in my day.

As a disabled person, independence has been integral to the way I flourish and interact with the world.

Independence can come in many forms, and it looks different for everybody.

Some ways that I am independent are using a light ‘SMAer’ cup to drink soup at a restaurant instead of needing someone to help me with a spoon so I don’t spill it on the way to my mouth… or finding a product that allows me to hold Ari during a dance party or pool day.

Not to mention accessibility features I use on my phone and in my apartment!

Accessibility and innovation are honestly so vital to my livelihood, and how I interact with the world as a disabled person and as a disabled mom.

I know you all have wanted me to share products that help me care for Ari, so here’s one of my favs so far!

I’ll link it in my bio 🙌🏼💕🌻

(if any of you watch my stories, you know that she lives in her sunbonnet! Yes, because it protects her from the sun, but also because it is the cutest thing in the entire world 🥹 I just took it  off for the few minutes we were enjoying the view on the rooftop while I was driving around with her!)

My disabled hand holding my baby.

My baby that is already physically stronger than me.

Me, holding her on the outside.
So close to where I held her on the inside.

The beauty in that is mesmerizing.
Powerful, vulnerable, and raw.

My disabled hand, holding her life.

‘You can’t even move her headband, you shouldn’t be a mom’

Needing help with aspects of my daughters care does not make me unworthy of parenthood. If her needs are being met, that is facilitated with my prompting, I’m caring for her. Disabled people have care assistants that essentially act as a extension of us — helping with the tasks we can’t physically do due to our disability.

This is the same for disabled parenthood.

Being disabled DOES NOT make you unworthy of being a parent.

Just like the fact that I can’t prepare my own food doesn’t mean I don’t eat — because I can’t change a diaper doesn’t mean my daughters diaper doesn’t get changed.

The ableism that society inflicts on disabled parents is horrendous. Meanwhile, people who utilize daycare, Nannie’s, and employees who care for their child aren’t looked at any different in regards to be a parent. When a disabled person hires a nanny to facilitate the care of their child due to disability — they’re unworthy of parenthood.

I urge you to reframe this mindset, as it’s deeply rooted in ableism.

Disabled people are worthy of parenthood, love, and living a life they want✨

All bodies are summer bodies ✨🫶🏼🌻

Including disabled bodies.
The ones that go unseen, many times.

The ones that are marginalized by society.
The ones that are seen as ‘unattractive.’

Don’t let the media fool you. Just because you don’t see your body type represented, you ARE worthy of wearing that swimmie.

The only requirement of having a summer body is existing, in the summer… wearing whatever makes YOU feel confident 🌞

I’m my OWN representation & I feel cute as heck in my disabled, postpartum summer body.

And you can too, xo

‘Who did that to her’ … talking about me being pregnant. Disabled people have sex, relationships, and children. We chose this journey TOGETHER 💓

The stigma associated with a non disabled person being with a visibly disabled person is so prevalent, especially on social media.

We are here to #breakthestigma 💕

Also, HER SMILE 🥹😩
He said it was a day for the books 💓 we love celebrating dad & all he does for us ✨ Also can we talk about how much more comfortable he is handling her now vs her NICU days 🥹🫶🏼
Favorite part of my day is seeing that beautiful smile 🥹🥰💓
Sundays are for mommy daughter cuddles and home cooked meals 🫶🏼
Her little feet 🥰 She loves her lion rattle 🦁
Happy Fourth of July 🇺🇸🎉 old faces, new memories 🫶🏼
My little lady will be 4 months tomorrow 🥹🫶🏼 time flies so fast she is getting so big and my heart can’t take it! disregard the spit up on my shirt 😆

I’m still processing trauma.

It’s not spoken about a lot on here — the trauma that us who choose to share our lives publicly endure on a daily basis.

Being told you’re the worst person ever. That you’re nothing. That you shouldn’t be here. That you aren’t deserving of love, a job, a partner, or a child.

Because of the way they perceive you from the posts you’ve made over the years, with only the best intentions and heart.

Because of my public social media presence, the state has been at my front door — asking me invasive questions about my ability to parent.

“It’s just a comment, ignore the haters.”

When that hate is quite literally knocking on your front door, that creates a traumatic experience.

It creates stress on families.

And it’s not okay.
And I haven’t been okay.

There’s no excuse for hatred, bullying, and harassment. Regardless of someone’s follower count.

If you wouldn’t say it to someone’s face, it shouldn’t be left in someone’s comment section.

I’m processing the trauma.
I am a strong disabled mom.

Happy disability pride month 🎉
I created some merch to celebrate - link in bio ✨
Don’t forget to put on your sunscreen 🌞
Summertime in Chicago 🌞

I am confident in my disabled body. AH! My quote live in NYC! What an amazing way to celebrate disability pride month. Beyond excited to announce my recent collaboration with @wally , as we set out on a quest to radiate positivity worldwide. Each month, we’ll be bringing to life various walls in diverse locations with uplifting quotes. Our goal? To invigorate and elevate our communities, both in the physical and digital world. Join us as we infuse the universe with good vibes! #GoodVibesMovement #Wally
Happiness in a post 🌞💕✨🌻
All the kisses for our little miss ♥️

As we wrap up Disability Pride Month, we are ecstatic to be spreading disabled joy with our content… and our merch! We meet so many of you when we are walking down the street and it truly makes us so happy to have so much support and meet you all in person as well!

Our little family is so thankful for all the support, and that despite the hundreds of hate comments we get on a daily basis we do have supporters out there that find value in our content and message.

That disabled folks find love, have families, and find pride in how our lives intersect with disability.

We are beyond exciting to be sending out SO many orders this month and we want to thank everyone for the kindness & support whether that’s transcended through leaving a kind comment or buying our merch — we are so thankful.

Our little lady is so loved and we feel that so much when you congratulate us in public.

Anyways, just want to say thank you. Sometimes we can lose sight of all the lovely humans that support us when hate is so prevalent in our comments. As I see you all in public and see your smiling faces, it was a true reminder of why we are here: to create community and break stigmas.

If we’ve seen you in public, it was an absolute pleasure meeting you — it’s brightened my day to when I was in an otherwise dark place. So thank you.

& if you grabbed our merch, please post and tag us so we can thank you!

#disabilitypridemonth

She’s back 💕

I started this social media journey talking about disabled bodies — how they’re sexy, valuable, and worthy of being seen.

All these years later, I’m a mom.

I’ve struggled with my identity with my new life… who am I? What do I want to share? What am I passionate about?

The answer was much more simple than what I thought was a winding road of endless pursuit to find peace in an answer.

I am still Alex, the one who talks about disabled bodies, disability justice, and breaking stereotypes.

The one who loves hard.
Who is passionate and creative.

Now, I have a family. My life has changed, yes. But my passions remain the same — and being a mother has not changed that.

In fact, it’s added more. Another purpose. Another journey.

Another story to tell.

The hardest part of my pregnancy was not being able to swallow very well.

My disease, SMA, already has caused me a lot of weakening in my mouth, tongue, and throat muscles that allow for swallowing.

Without treatment, swallowing for me had gotten progressively worse as I’ve aged. I remember being little, chowing down on steak and ribs and enjoying the heck out of it — something I can’t do as an adult due to weakened throat muscles.

When I started treatment for SMA, my swallow drastically improved, reinvigorating my foodie nature that was dormant for so long.

For years while on two different treatments at separate times, I was able to enjoy foods I haven’t been able to enjoy in years.

During my pregnancy, I had to put my foodie joy on hold, as I had to stop treatment which made me progressively more weak. Some days, between how weak I got and my morning sickness, I was lucky to get in a few crackers.

To accommodate my weak swallow, I lived off soup, mainly @panerabread broccoli cheese 🧀 

Even on treatment, meats are usually tough to eat. Here I am on the right 6 months after giving birth, feeling strong, back on treatment, enjoying a huge fully loaded burger 🍔 

In foodie heaven if you will 🥹
The days I could barely swallow are gone, but it made me sit and enjoy the hell out of this burger.

And now I have a new appreciation for @panerabread , too. 💓

Your mobility aid does not make you any less worthy or appealing.

I remember when I was in college, I would sometimes dream about finding my true love one day and what it would look like waking up next to them. I thought about how my BiPAP and my ear donut would make sleeping next to me unappealing.

I thought about all the movies I have seen and how a couple would be in bed cuddling together and how that did not at all resemble my reality.

here I am using mobility devices that make me comfortable and allow me to breathe during the night, and I am thinking about some hypothetical scenario based on what I have seen in movies.

Crazy, right?

I don’t think so. I think a lot of us have carry these insecurities when we do not feel seen or accepted.

To my surprise, no one ever seemed to mind my mobility aids at all.

The power of how you perceive yourself is incredibly strong. I wish I gave myself earlier opportunities to invite people in, knowing my mobility aids weren’t objectively unattractive. But, it took me years.

But, that’s okay. Progress is progress.

As long as we continue on the journey, that’s all we can do 💓

“ But lately I’ve been living in comment sections “

This is how I look when I go to sleep. And there is no shame in that. I wear a CPAP at night to make sure that I am breathing properly while I am asleep. A fun fact about my CPAP is that a lot of people assume that it provides oxygen at night, but it is controlled by settings put in place by my pulmonologist, and it only pushes room air into my lungs. From an outside viewpoint, it might look quite uncomfortable and it has definitely taken a lot of trial and error to find the perfect placement of the mask for the best comfort level while I am asleep. Because I do not move at all while I am sleeping, I am prone to getting a pressure sore if this side of the mask isn’t perfectly placed on my head. So when I am putting it on at night, it is a lot of “a little bit this way, a little bit that way!” Because I do not move in my sleep I also am prone to pressure sores on my ear, which is why I use an ear donut! For years I had this special foam, I don’t even remember where I got it, and I would make a homemade one and cut a hole in the very perfect spot, so that there was not too much pressure on any part of of my head. As of recently, I have found the perfect ear donut after having an immense amount of anxiety that this special foam was running out, and I wouldn’t be able to continue making the perfect ear donut. I remember thinking, I am so screwed when this damn foam runs out lol. So, I started buying pretty much every type of ear donut on Amazon until I found the perfect one that works with my comfort and my CPAP! As a disabled person, little things as simple as this can honestly make or break your comfort. I miss telling you all about my little accessibility/disability hacks, and things I do in my daily life to make my life easier and more comfortable!

💘team comfort💘

WHO IS HERE FOR THE AL COOKING CONTENT?!

all jokes aside, cooking is one of my passions and I have spent a great deal of my free time since I was a teenager watching Food Network and various cooking shows.

One thing that I was so excited about with having a daughter was the ability to share my love of cooking and food with her.

I absolutely love getting inspired and making something I see on my feed or on TV my own.

A lot of times when I have mentioned, I cooked something, I get comments saying that I did not do it because I wasn’t the one that physically cut up the ingredients and put them together & I need to give the other person the ‘credit.’

this is a textbook ableist mindset.

A caregiver, family, or friend who is helping a disabled person facilitate an activity or task that they want to do is just that, they are helping us facilitate and live our lives. That isn’t to say that they don’t deserve any recognition, they most certainly do! No one is saying that they aren’t the ones who are helping. But, disabled people deserve to be recognized as autonomous humans that require the help of others at times.

requiring assistance to facilitate a task or activity, does not diminish the disabled person, and what they are contributing to the activity.

I am so excited to hopefully break some ableism and give you guys some of my favorite recipes with some cooking content 💓🫶🏼
